/PG424/XX/PR
/KASEDER BIRKAT HAH/±ODESH //PR
/XXBLESSING OF THE NEW MONTH/PR
/ITOn the Shabbat before Rosh H/±odesh, the Torah is lifted and the following is said:/PR
/PR
May it be your will, /SCE/XXTERNAL /XXO/XXNE/XX, our God, God of our
ancestors, that you renew for us this month, for goodness and
for blessing. May you give to us long life, a life of peace, a life
of goodness, a life of blessing, a life of nourishment and
sustenance. May it be a life of bodily health, a life in which is
found awe for the divine, a life in which we have a love of Torah
and fear of heaven, a life free of disgrace and shame, a life of
happiness and honor, a life of integrity and discernment,
intelligence and knowledge, a life in which our heartÚs petitions
are fulfilled for goodness. Amen./PI/PR
/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. There is a tradition that each Rosh H/±odesh is a
èàó òÖîã çÖâ / "little Yom Kippur." About two hundred years ago the simple
announcement of the time of the new moon was amplified to the Blessing
of the New Month to include that point of view. That is why petitionary
phrases appear in the /ITberah/±ah/XX despite the fact that such petitions are not
normally allowed on Shabbat.    /SC/XXE.M./XX/PR
